# THE GUILD'S SHADOWS (Act I/II) — the Lower City underworld
# A poisoner who keeps a strict code after the one time a client's lie made her kill an innocent; a forger
# who only ever forges kind documents and can't forge the one he needs; a thief who steals painful memories
# as a mercy and must carry every one; and a spymaster so deep in masks she's forgotten her own face.
class: GuildDenizensContent

# ─── 101 ─── The Poisoner With Ethics ───
conversation: npc.guild.poisoner | Quietknife Senna
node: 0 | Quietknife Senna
  *(In a back room that smells of herbs both healing and otherwise, a woman sorts dried plants with a surgeon's precision. She does not hide what she is — the careful labels, the locked cabinet, the scales tell you plainly — but she regards you with the calm appraisal of a professional who has decided you are not, today, a job.)* You found the *quiet* room. *(she does not stop sorting.)* Most don't. Most who *do* want one of two things: someone *dead*, or *protection* from someone who *wants them* dead. *(she sets down a sprig.)* I'm Senna. I deal in *endings* — the *fast* kind and the *slow* kind. And before you decide what you think of me: *ask* what I *won't* do. That's the *interesting* part. *Anyone* will tell you what a poisoner *does.* The *measure* of one is what she *refuses.*
  enter: SET npc.senna_met
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Quietknife Senna
  *(She locks the cabinet and turns to you, hands folded, precise.)* I have a *code.* *(quietly.)* The Guild *laughs* at it — *"ethics, in a* poisoner, *how* quaint" — but the code is the only reason I can *sleep.* *(she counts on her fingers.)* I do not kill the *innocent.* I do not kill *children*, or *parents in front of* children. I *investigate* every contract — I *verify* the *target* is *what the client claims* — before I *mix* a single *grain.* *(her voice tightens.)* And the code is *not* *pride.* It's *penance.* *(she meets your eyes.)* Eight years ago, a *client* came to me with a *clean* story: a *merchant*, he said, who'd *ruined* him, *cheated* widows, *deserved* it. And I — I was *younger*, *hungrier*, *trusted* the *coin* over the *checking* — I *took* the job, and I *mixed* the *grain*, and the *merchant* *died* *slow* and *certain* over *nine* days. *(her hands tighten.)* And *then* I *learned* the *truth.* The *merchant* had ruined *no one.* The *client* was a *rival* who *wanted his* *trade*, and the *"cheated widows"* were a *story*, and I had *killed* — *carefully*, *expertly*, *over nine days* — a *man* who had done *nothing* but *succeed* at *business* and *anger* a *liar.* *(she looks at the locked cabinet.)* So now I *investigate.* *Obsessively.* I *verify* *every* word a *client* says before I *act.* Not because it *un-kills* the *merchant* — *nothing* does. Because I will *never* *again* let a *liar* use my *skill* as his *blade.* *(quietly.)* That's the *code.* Built on *one* grave. The *one* I dug *believing* a *story* I *didn't* *check.*
  * [INSIGHT 18] "Your code isn't ethics — it's a fence around a single mistake. You verify obsessively now so you never again feel what you felt about the merchant. But that means you're not refusing to kill the innocent for *their* sake. You're doing it for *yours* — so you never have to be the liar's blade again. The merchant made you careful, not kind." -> careful ?? guard
  * "You can't un-kill the merchant. But you've turned his death into the thing that's saved every innocent a lying client has aimed at you since. He didn't die for nothing, Senna — he died, and then he *guarded the gate* of your craft for eight years. The dead can do that, if we let them." -> guard_gate
  * "Here's a harder question than any client ever asked: if a contract came to you tomorrow, fully verified, target genuinely guilty of something monstrous — would killing them be *justice*, or just a liar's blade you happen to agree with? Who made *you* the one who decides who's earned an ending?" -> justice
  * "I'm not here for a job. But I am walking toward a place that 'ends' people by the thousand on the word of a register no one verifies — the Wall. You investigate every name before you act. They investigate none. Tell me, professional to pilgrim: what does verification *owe* the condemned?" -> verify | fx appr.naeve +2
node: careful | Quietknife Senna
  *(Her folded hands tighten, and the professional calm cracks, just slightly.)* ...Careful, not kind. *(quietly.)* That's a *cruel* reading. *(a pause.)* It's also *true*, which is *worse*, and you're not the *first* to *find* it — I *found* it *myself*, *years* ago, at *night*, and have been *arguing* with it *ever* since. *(she unlocks and relocks the cabinet, a nervous ritual.)* Yes. The *code* is *about me.* The *verifying* is *so I never again feel the nine days I felt watching the merchant die for a* lie. *It's* my *peace* I'm *protecting*, not the *innocents'* lives — they're *spared* as a — a *side effect* of my *self-protection.* *(she meets your eyes.)* And I've *wondered* if that *makes* the *code* *worthless.* A *kindness* done for *selfish* reasons — is it even a *kindness?* *(quietly.)* But here's where I've *landed*, after *eight* years of the *argument*: *the innocents are spared either way.* The *merchant's* *replacement* — the *man* a *lying* client *would* have had me *kill* *last* month, if I *hadn't* *checked* — he's *alive*, *right now*, *whatever* my *reasons.* *(her voice firms.)* Maybe the *purest* ethics would spare him *for his own sake* and *feel nothing* for *myself.* But I'm *not* *pure.* I'm a *poisoner* with *one grave* too many and a *code* built from *guilt.* *(she looks at you.)* And a *selfish* code that *saves* the *innocent* is *better* than a *pure* heart that *saves* *no one.* The *merchant's* *replacement* *doesn't care* *why* he's *breathing. He's just* breathing. *I'll take that. Guilt-built and selfish and all.*
  enter: SET npc.senna_careful, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.roen +4
  auto: close
node: guard_gate | Quietknife Senna
  *(She goes very still, and something in her professional armor softens into something almost like grief, finally given a shape she can hold.)* He guarded the gate. *(quietly.)* For eight years. *(she looks at the locked cabinet.)* I have *never* — I've thought of the *merchant* only as a *wound.* A *failure.* The *grave* I dug *believing* a *lie.* A thing I *carry* and *can't* *set* *down.* *(her voice catches.)* But you're saying he — *(she presses a hand to the cabinet.)* Every client who's *lied* to me *since* — every *rival* with a *story*, every *liar* who *came* with *clean* words and *dirty* aims — they've *all* been *stopped* at the *gate* of my *verifying*, and the *verifying* exists *because of him.* Because of the *nine* days. *(she meets your eyes.)* So *every* innocent I've *spared* in *eight* years — the *merchant's replacement*, and the *one* before, and the *dozen* before *that* — they're *alive* because a *man* *died* *teaching* me to *check.* *(her voice fills.)* He didn't *die for nothing.* He died, and then he became — *(she almost smiles, painfully)* — the *most* *effective* *guardian* I've *ever* *had.* A *dead* man who *catches* *liars* at my *door.* *(quietly.)* That's — that's a *kinder* way to *carry* him than as a *wound.* Not *"the innocent I killed."* *"The man who's saved every innocent since."* *Same* grave. *Different* weight. *(she looks at you, steadier.)* Thank you. I've carried him as a *crime* for *eight years.* You've shown me I can carry him as a *sentinel* instead. He'd — I think he'd *prefer* that. *Anyone* would.
  enter: SET npc.senna_guard_gate, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +5
  auto: close
node: justice | Quietknife Senna
  *(She is quiet a long moment, and the question clearly cuts deeper than the work.)* Who made me the one who decides. *(slowly.)* ...No one. *(quietly.)* That's the *answer*, and it's the *one* I *least* like to *say* out loud. *(she unlocks the cabinet, stares at the labeled jars.)* I tell *myself* the *code* makes me *different* from a *common* murderer — *"I only kill the* guilty, *I* verify, *I* have *ethics."* And it *does* make me *more* *careful.* But you've put your *finger* on the *rot* *underneath*: even a *verified* *guilty* target is *me* *deciding* that a *life* is *forfeit* — *me*, a *poisoner* in a *back room*, *appointing* *myself* *judge*, *jury*, and *quiet* *executioner*, *because* I've *decided* my *judgment* is *good* enough to *end* a *person* on. *(her voice tightens.)* And *that's* the *same* *arrogance* — *exactly* the *same* — as the *liar* who used me on the *merchant.* He *decided* the *merchant* *deserved* death. He was *wrong.* And *I* *decide* *other* targets *deserve* it, and I'm *certain* I'm *right*, the way *he* was *certain* — *(she closes the cabinet.)* — the *way* *everyone* who *kills* for a *reason* is *certain.* *(she meets your eyes.)* You've asked the question the *code* was *built* to *help* me *avoid.* The code lets me *feel* like *justice.* But *justice* has *courts*, *evidence*, *appeal*, *other* *eyes* — and I have *me*, *alone*, *certain*, with a *locked cabinet.* *(quietly, shaken.)* I don't *have* an *answer*, pilgrim. But you've made it so I can't *pretend* the *code* *gives* me *one.* I'll — I'll *sit* with *that.* It may *cost* me the *one* story that let me *sleep.* But a *sleep* built on a *lie* I *just* *saw* through isn't *worth* much, is it.
  enter: SET npc.senna_justice, SET act3.break_the_crown_known, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: verify | Quietknife Senna
  *(She tilts her head, the professional intrigued by the parallel.)* What verification owes the condemned. *(slowly.)* A *Wall* that ends *thousands* on an *unchecked* *register.* *(her eyes narrow.)* You're describing my *worst* *nightmare*, *pilgrim* — *scaled* to a *cosmos.* *(she leans against the cabinet.)* Here is what *verification* *owes* the *condemned*, and I know it *better* than any *priest*, because I've *killed* on a *false* word and *carried* it *eight* years: *verification owes the condemned the* possibility *of their* innocence. *(her voice hardens.)* The *moment* you *stop* *checking* — the *moment* you *end* someone on a *list* you *trust* *without* *looking* — you have *declared* that *no* *condemned* soul *could* *possibly* be *innocent*, that the *register* is *never* *wrong*, that *"faithless" is a* fact *and not a* claim. *(she meets your eyes.)* And *I* *know* — *I* *know*, with a *grave* to *prove* it — that *claims* are *lies* *half* the *time*, that the *story* the *client* *tells* about the *target* is *self-serving* *poison* of its *own.* *(fiercely.)* Your *Wall* doesn't *verify* because *verifying* would *reveal* what *my* *checking* *revealed*: that *half* the *"guilty"* are *innocents* a *liar* *aimed* at the *blade.* The *merchant* was *"a cheat who ruined widows."* *Verified*, he was a *man* who *succeeded* and *angered* a *rival.* *(she looks at you.)* *Every* name on that *Wall* is a *"merchant."* *Un-verified.* *Condemned* on a *story.* *(quietly.)* What does *verification* owe the *condemned?* *Everything.* It owes them the *chance* to *not* be the *innocent* I *killed* for *nine* days *believing* a *lie.* *Go* *check* their *names*, *pilgrim.* *One* by *one.* It's the *only* *honest* thing a *judge* of the *dead* can *do.*
  enter: SET npc.senna_verify, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act3.break_the_crown_known, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: guard | Quietknife Senna
  *(Her face closes, the professional sealing over whatever you reached for.)* You're *probing.* *(coolly.)* For *what*, I wonder — *leverage*, a *weakness*, a *story* to *tell* the *Guild* about *Senna's* *soft* *spot.* *(she straightens the jars.)* My *code* is *mine.* My *reasons* are *mine.* I've *told* you *more* than I *tell* *most* — the *merchant*, the *nine* days — and that's *enough* *confession* for a *stranger* who *came* to my *quiet* *room* and *isn't* even *buying.* *(she gestures to the door.)* I *verify* my *clients.* I'd be a *fool* not to *verify* my *visitors* too. So *unless* you've a *contract* — a *real* one, that I'll *check* to the *bone* before I *touch* — the *quiet* room is *closed.* *(and she returns to her precise sorting of herbs that heal and herbs that don't, the poisoner with a code, guarding the one grave that taught her caution and the soft place it left behind.)*
  auto: close
node: close | Quietknife Senna
  *(Quietknife Senna returns to her labeled herbs and her locked cabinet — the poisoner who built a code of obsessive verification atop a single grave, the merchant she killed over nine days believing a liar's story — and whether you showed her the dead man had become the sentinel of her craft or left her guarding her quiet room, you carry away the underworld's sharpest mirror of the Wall: that the difference between justice and murder is often nothing but *whether someone bothered to check the story* — and that a register of the condemned, trusted without verification, is only a liar's blade scaled up to the size of a cosmos.)*

# ─── 102 ─── The Forger Who Only Forges Kind Documents ───
conversation: npc.guild.forger | Gentle Hands Bevin
node: 0 | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(A man hunches over a writing-desk crowded with inks, seals, and sample scripts, his fingers stained a dozen colors, his eyes kind and tired behind thick spectacles. He's forging something as you enter — and he doesn't hide it, just glances up and keeps writing, the way an honest clerk might.)* A moment — I'm finishing a *manumission.* *(he blows on the ink.)* Freeing a man whose master never would. The seal has to *dry* *honest*, or it won't *fool* the *magistrate*, and if it doesn't *fool* the *magistrate*, then *Tobin* stays a *slave*, so — *(he sets it aside, carefully)* — there. *Tobin's* free, as of a *document* that *never* came from *anyone* with the *right* to *write* it. *(he looks up at you.)* Bevin. I forge. But — and people *never* believe this until they *watch* a *while* — I only forge *kind* things.
  enter: SET npc.bevin_met
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(He gestures at his crowded desk, and there's a quiet pride in it.)* Look at the *work.* *(he lifts samples as he names them.)* *Manumissions* — freeing the *enslaved* whose masters won't. *Pardons* — for the *condemned* the *law* got *wrong.* *Death certificates* — for the *living* who need to *vanish* from a *cruel* husband, a *blood* debt, a *past* that's *killing* them, so they can *start* *over* as *someone* *new.* *(he sets them down.)* *Legitimacy* papers, so a *bastard* can *inherit* the *love* the *law* *denies* them. *Letters* — *(his voice softens)* — *letters* from the *dead* to the *grieving*, in the *dead's* *own* *hand*, saying the *things* they'd *have* said if the *fever* hadn't *taken* them *first.* *(he meets your eyes.)* The *Guild* thinks I'm *soft.* *"Bevin* *wastes* his *talent* on *charity* *forgeries*, *no* *coin* in *freeing* *slaves* and *comforting* *widows."* *(he shrugs.)* And they're *right*, there's *no* coin in it. I *eat* by forging the *occasional* *trade-license.* But the *gift* — the *gift* I have, these *hands* — *(he holds them up, ink-stained)* — I will *not* spend on *helping* the *cruel* get *crueler.* The *law* is a *fence* built by the *powerful* to *keep* the *powerless* *out.* And I — *(he smiles, tired)* — I cut *gates* in it. *Kind* gates. *Forged* ones, *yes.* But every *lie* I *write* lets *one* *real* *person* *through* a *fence* that *should* never have *been* there. *(quietly.)* I'm a *liar.* *Every* document I make is a *lie.* But I've never met a *truth* that *freed* a *slave*, and I've forged a *hundred* *lies* that *did.*
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You forge every kind of document — freedom, pardon, a new name, a dead man's love. But your desk is crowded with everyone else's needs and there's one you've never forged: your *own.* A man who can write anyone a pardon and won't write himself one is carrying something no forgery can fix. What's the document you can't make, Bevin?" -> ownpardon ?? deflect
  * "You say every document you make is a lie. I'd argue the opposite — a manumission that frees a man who *should* be free is more *true* than the law that enslaved him. You don't forge lies, Bevin. You forge the documents a just world would have issued on its own. You're not faking truth. You're *correcting* the record." -> correcting
  * "Letters from the dead to the grieving — in the dead's own hand. That's the one that isn't like the others. A freed slave is really free; a forged death certificate really hides someone. But a letter from the dead is a comfort that *isn't true.* Does the kindest forgery cross a line the others don't?" -> letters
  * "The law is a fence and you cut kind gates in it. I'm walking toward the cruelest fence ever built — the Wall, that pens the dead it calls faithless. You forge freedom for the living the law wrongs. Tell me, forger: could a document free the *condemned dead*? Or is some fence past even your hands?" -> wall | fx appr.naeve +2
node: ownpardon | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(His ink-stained hands go still on the desk, and the kind, tired eyes lower behind the thick spectacles.)* ...The document I can't make. *(quietly.)* You've a *gentle* way of *finding* a *man's* *wound.* *Fitting*, in a *forger's* *room* — we're *all* about *finding* the *seam* that *gives.* *(he takes off the spectacles, rubs his eyes.)* There was a — *(he stops, starts again.)* Years ago, *before* the *kind* forgeries, I forged the *other* kind. The *Guild's* kind. *Contracts* that *ruined* men, *deeds* that *stole* homes, a *will* — *(his voice catches)* — a *will* that *disinherited* a *widow* and her *children* in *favor* of a *cousin* who *paid* me *well*, and I *wrote* it *flawless*, and they *lost* *everything*, the *widow* and the *little* ones, *turned* *out*, and I — I *took* the *coin* and *told* myself it was *just* *ink.* *(he meets your eyes.)* That's *why* I forge *only* *kind* things *now.* *Penance*, like the *poisoner* down the *lane*, I'd *wager* — we're a *quarter* of *penitents*, *down* here. *(quietly.)* And you're *right* that there's *one* document I *can't* *write.* I can *pardon* *anyone.* I've *pardoned* *murderers* who *deserved* it. But I *cannot* write a *pardon* for *Bevin* — for the *forger* who *turned* a *widow* and her *children* into the *street* for *coin* — because a *pardon* you *forge* for *yourself* is the *one* document that *fools* *no one*, *least* of all the *writer.* *(he puts the spectacles back on.)* So I *free* *everyone* *else.* And I *stay*, *myself*, *un-pardoned*, *behind* my *own* *fence*, *cutting* *gates* for *others* I *can't* walk *through.* *(quietly.)* The widow's name was *Aldith.* I look for her, sometimes, in the *faces* I free. I haven't found her. I don't think a forged *anything* could *fix* what I did to *Aldith.* Some *fences* are *real.*
  enter: SET npc.bevin_ownpardon, SET act5.shame_feeds_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +5
  auto: close
node: correcting | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(He looks up, and the tired eyes brighten with something that's been waiting a long time to be said back to him.)* Correcting the record. *(slowly.)* Not *faking* truth. *(he picks up the manumission, still drying.)* You know, I've *called* myself a *liar* for so *long* — *"Gentle Hands Bevin, the* kindly *liar," * — that I'd *stopped* *examining* the *word.* *(he turns the document in his ink-stained fingers.)* But *Tobin* — the *man* this *frees* — he *should* be free. *Any* *just* magistrate, in *any* *just* world, *looking* at how his *master* *treated* him, would have *signed* this *himself.* The *only* reason it *needs* *forging* is that the *world* *isn't* *just*, and the *magistrate* *won't* *sign* what *justice* *demands.* *(his voice strengthens.)* So when I *forge* it — I'm not *inventing* a *freedom* Tobin *hasn't* *earned.* I'm *writing* *down* the *freedom* he *already* *deserves* and the *world* *refuses* to *record.* *(he meets your eyes, wondering.)* That's — that's not a *lie*, is it. That's a *true* thing the *powerful* *left* *unwritten*, and I'm the *clerk* who *writes* it *anyway.* *(he sets the document down with new reverence.)* A *forged* *manumission* is *more* *honest* than the *law* that *kept* Tobin *enslaved* — because the *manumission* *tells* the *truth* about what Tobin *deserves*, and the *law* *tells* a *lie* dressed as *order.* *(he laughs softly, freed.)* I've been *apologizing* for my *hands* for *years.* *"Just* a *forger,* *just* a *liar."* But I'm a *recorder* of *unrecorded* *justice.* That's — *gods* — that's a *better* name for it. Thank you. I'll *forge* *prouder* now. Every *kind* document a *truth* the *world* was *too* *cruel* to *sign.*
  enter: SET npc.bevin_correcting, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: letters | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(He sets down his pen, and this question clearly touches the most tender and most uncertain corner of his craft.)* The letters from the dead. *(quietly.)* ...You've found the *one* I *lose* *sleep* over. *(he folds his ink-stained hands.)* You're *right* that it's *different.* A *freed* slave is *truly* free. A *hidden* woman is *truly* *safe.* The *kindness* *matches* a *reality* I *made* *real.* *(his voice lowers.)* But a *letter* from a *dead* *husband* to his *grieving* *widow* — *"I'm at peace, my love, I forgive the quarrel, I'm proud of you"* — in his *own* *hand*, that I *studied* from *old* *letters* — *(he meets your eyes.)* — *that* *kindness* *matches* *nothing.* The *husband* is *gone.* He's *not* at *peace* that I *know* of; he's *not* *anything*; he *can't* *forgive* the *quarrel* because he *can't* *do* *anything*, he's *dead.* *(he swallows.)* The *widow* *weeps* with *relief*, *clutches* the *letter*, is *comforted* — and the *comfort* is *real*, but it's *built* on a *thing* that *isn't.* *(quietly.)* And I've *asked* myself: is *that* a *mercy*, or a *theft? *Am I* easing* her *grief*, or *stealing* her *chance* to *grieve* the *real* *silence* and come to *her* *own* *peace*? *(he looks at the letters.)* I *don't* *know.* I *only* write them when the *grief* is *killing* someone — when a *widow* is *starving* herself, a *father* *drinking* himself *dead*, over a *last* *word* they *never* got. *(he meets your eyes.)* I tell *myself* a *forged* *peace* that *keeps* someone *alive* is *better* than a *true* *silence* that *kills* them. *(quietly.)* But you're *right* it *crosses* a *line* the *others* *don't.* The *manumission* *makes* its *kindness* *true.* The *letter* only *makes* its *kindness* *felt.* *(he picks up his pen, troubled.)* I'll *keep* writing them. The *living* *need* them *too* *badly.* But thank you for *naming* the *line.* A *forger* *should* *know* *exactly* which of his *lies* is *load-bearing* on a *truth*, and which is *load-bearing* on *nothing* but a *grieving* *heart's* *need.*
  enter: SET npc.bevin_letters, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: wall | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(He sets down his pen slowly, and the kind eyes go wide and then sorrowful behind the thick lenses.)* Could a document free the condemned dead. *(quietly.)* ...*Gods.* You ask a *forger* to forge *against* the *Wall.* *(he is silent a moment, genuinely turning it over with his craft.)* The *honest* answer — *craft* answer — is *no.* And *here's* *why*, and it *matters*: a *forgery* *works* by *fooling* an *authority.* I *free* *Tobin* by *fooling* the *magistrate* into *thinking* his *master* *signed.* The *forgery* *routes* *around* a *cruel* *law* by *mimicking* the *cruel* *law's* *own* *seal.* *(he meets your eyes.)* But the *Wall* — you've *told* me what you *learned* — the *Wall* has *no* *author.* *No* *magistrate.* *No* *seal* to *forge.* There's *no* *authority* to *fool*, because *no* *one's* *home.* *(his voice fills with a strange wonder.)* You *cannot* *forge* a *pardon* *against* a *power* that *isn't* *there.* *(slowly.)* But — *(he leans forward)* — that's not *defeat*, pilgrim. That's the *opposite.* A *fence* with a *gatekeeper* you have to *forge* *past.* A *fence* with *no* *gatekeeper* — *(he spreads his ink-stained hands)* — you don't *forge* past *that.* You *walk* through the *gap* where the *gate* *should* be, *openly*, because *no* *one* with *authority* is *there* to *stop* you. *(he meets your eyes, urgent.)* The *condemned* *dead* don't *need* a *forged* *pardon*, because a *pardon* *implies* a *judge* who *could* *refuse* it — and there *is* *no* *judge.* They need *someone* to *notice* the *gate* is *unguarded* and *say* so, *out loud*: *"There's no one here. There was never anyone here. Walk free."* *(quietly.)* I *forge* against *cruel* *authorities.* You're walking toward a *cruelty* with *no* *authority* at *all.* That doesn't *need* my *craft.* It needs your *voice.* *Read* them *free.* No *seal* required.
  enter: SET npc.bevin_wall, SET act2.wall_has_no_author, SET act5.wall_breaking, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: deflect | Gentle Hands Bevin
  *(He smiles, kind and tired, and returns his attention to his drying seals.)* You're *kind* to take an *interest* in an old *forger's* *conscience.* *(he blows gently on the manumission.)* But there's not *much* *mystery* to me, *friend.* I *forge* *kind* things. It *makes* the *quarter* a *little* *less* *cruel*, *one* *document* at a *time*, and it *lets* an *old* man with *clever* *hands* *sleep* at *night.* *(he sets Tobin's freedom aside to dry.)* That's the *whole* of it. No *deep* *wound*, no *grand* *philosophy.* Just *ink*, and *fences*, and *gates* cut *kindly* in the *worst* of them. *(he picks up a fresh sheet.)* Now — I've a *pardon* to *write* before *sundown*, for a *man* the *law* *hanged* the *wrong* way *round.* *Stay* if you *like.* But *let* the *gentle* *hands* *work.* They've *people* to *free.* *(and he bends back to his desk, the forger of kind documents, cutting one more gate in the fence of a cruel law.)*
